  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Hutukara Associa&#xE7;&#xE3;o Yanomami (HAY) - Indigenous Rights and Institutional Strengthening</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The aim of this project is to strengthen Hutukara Yanomami Association&#x2019;s (HAY) presence in grassroots indigenous communities, in order to protect and manage Yanomami Indigenous Territory (TIY) and contribute to the full recognition and implementation of collective rights for the Yanomami and Ye&#x2019;kuana indigenous people.

The Yanomami and Ye&apos;kuana people were officially granted rights to TIY in 1992, however land invasions continue, such as illegal gold-miners and farmers, and communities are increasingly impacted by climate change, which are affecting their health, food security and environment. Other key challenges include inadequate health service provision, lack of access to quality bi-lingual education and the need for indigenous cultural preservation. 

HAY undertakes long distance communications and regional meetings with indigenous communities to identify the key threats and issues, and then uses this information to lobby key governmental bodies and advocate for public policies and the protection of indigenous rights. The three key outcomes are: 
1. HAY and communities increase their knowledge and are mobilised to defend indigenous rights;
2. 20 communities within TIY are engaged in debates on land management, protection and the effects of climate change;
3. HAY is strengthened in political representation, financial sustainability, and project management.</narrative>
  </description>
